    <h3 class="comment__title"><a href="/comment/779331#comment-779331" class="permalink" rel="bookmark">noise interference</a></h3>
  
  <div class="submitted subtext">
    Submitted by all4health on August 3, 2015 - 9:16am  </div>

  <div class="content">
    <div class="field field-name-comment-body field-type-text-long field-label-hidden">
        <div class="field__item"><p>I see the value in this article and discussion, sent to me by a physical therapist who is my sister. I'm an acupuncturist and Zero Balancer who has provided more than 300,000 treatments over 18 years. Excessive decibel levels trigger the anxiety responses you describe, and these are becoming ever more present in the US where over 25% of people under 19 now have hearing impairment. Loud noise in traffic raises women's heart attack and stroke risk by 300% and men's by 50%. Where I live and work, an outdoor concert venue of over 15,000 does not stay within legal decibel levels and these limits are not enforced effectively, if at all. So we are blasted in our homes for up to 12 hours at a time, and people nine miles away report hearing this venue. Doing every practice you list plus receiving weekly treatments barely keeps me able to work effectively. What research and support can you provide to convince local authorities to enforce the law and protect children, whose ear canals receive these emissions 20 decibels higher: 100 times as loud?</p>
</div>
