<a id="comment-821381"></a>
<div class="comment comment-by-anonymous clearfix">
  
    <h3 class="comment__title"><a href="/comment/821381#comment-821381" class="permalink" rel="bookmark">No thanks</a></h3>
  
  <div class="submitted subtext">
    Submitted by VictoriaJane on February 20, 2016 - 7:00am  </div>

  <div class="content">
    <div class="field field-name-comment-body field-type-text-long field-label-hidden">
        <div class="field__item"><p>Mr. Bergland writes: </p>
<p>"Of course, none of us like to be around high strung people, but it is particularly important when you need to have grace under pressure."</p>
<p>I beg to differ. I'm often drawn to high-strung people. Some of them are creative, "sensitive artist" types; some are original thinkers who get obsessive about ideas; some are just odd individuals who've led interesting lives. </p>
<p>Over the years, my list of friends, lovers, and acquaintances has included a bi-polar Ivy League philosophy professor, a schizo-affective street poet, and a depressed NASA scientist. My best friend is a successful software engineer who has mild OCD, chronic anxiety, and occasional paranoia. She's also the kindest, most generous, loyal, and honest person you could ever hope to meet. I love her to death. </p>
<p>"Easy-going" and "high strung" are different innate temperaments, not moral virtues and vices. The various high-strung types may suffer more emotionally; they may live on the border (or over the border) of the mental terrain we label as "pathological." But they can also be brilliant, courageous, inspired, and inspiring people. </p>
<p>Whatever "grace under pressure" I've personally achieved has involved those high strung people you're telling me to avoid. They've inspired some of my best creative work. They've shared my most memorable adventures. The times I've been able to help them are some of my proudest moments. </p>
<p>So thanks for the advice, but no, I don't think I'll put in my headphones to block out others' anxiety. Maybe I'll talk to the other people waiting nervously for the audition. Maybe I'll tell the guy behind me a witty joke to break the tension. Maybe I'll give the girl in front of me an understanding smile and tell her, "Yeah, I'm nervous too -- but wow! I love your shoes.."  And maybe we'll all go in feeling just a tiny bit better. THAT seems more like grace under pressure to me.</p>
<p>In short, if my vagal nerve needs to be distanced from other people's troubles and emotions, then I guess my vagal nerve will have to go f*** itself. My high strung friends and I won't really miss it.</p>
</div>
  </div>
      </div>

  <ul class="links inline"><li class="comment-reply first"><a href="/comment/reply/114896/821381">Reply to VictoriaJane</a></li>
<li class="quote last"><a href="/comment/reply/114896/821381?quote=1#comment-form" title="Quote this post in your reply.">Quote VictoriaJane</a></li>
</ul></div>

<div class="indented"><a id="comment-867678"></a>
<div class="comment comment-by-anonymous clearfix">
  
    <h3 class="comment__title"><a href="/comment/867678#comment-867678" class="permalink" rel="bookmark">Thank you for your comments</a></h3>
  
  <div class="submitted subtext">
    Submitted by MS on September 6, 2016 - 3:57pm  </div>

  <div class="content">
    <div class="field field-name-comment-body field-type-text-long field-label-hidden">
        <div class="field__item"><p>I really dislike the trend that separates people into two groups- the good and the bad. "How to deal with difficult people" "How to spot a narcissist" etc. If you ask me, all of our human characteristics occur on a continuum and there will be times,when all of us might not be a welcome presence for others. Labelling people as pathological in some respect provides criteria by which we can divide people into desirable and undesirable groups. This categorization flatters those who consider themselves to be members of the right groups. I think the whole way that we approach well-being is not helpful, and will never allowned for the destigmatization of "mental illness." In my opinion, a better approach will need to look at the circumstances that allow some to thrive and make these conditions available to all to the extent possible. Avoiding anxious people also seems to contradict loving kindness.</p>
</div>
  </div>
      </div>

