<a id="comment-861567"></a>
<div class="comment comment-by-anonymous clearfix">
  
    <h3 class="comment__title"><a href="/comment/861567#comment-861567" class="permalink" rel="bookmark">Vagus Nerve Stimulation</a></h3>
  
  <div class="submitted subtext">
    Submitted by Sam Milnes on August 8, 2016 - 4:58am  </div>

  <div class="content">
    <div class="field field-name-comment-body field-type-text-long field-label-hidden">
        <div class="field__item"><p>I didn't know the biological explanation for it at the time, but this exercise, deep diaphramatic breathing to stimulate the vagal response and slow the heart rate, was taught to me as a teenager, when I was practising target rifle shooting at school.<br />
Its purpose, I was told and went on to observe and understand - and become an award-winning shot for a time -  was to slow and steady the heart-beat for a few seconds, ready for the moment when the trigger is squeezed (not pulled!) at the moment when the breath is slowly expelled, and ensure a better and more consistent aim on the bulls-eye as the bullet leaves the rifle barrel.<br />
It wasn't called that then, but this was mindfuI shooting, and it really worked!  I am sure this technique could be used to advantage in many activities, sporting or otherwise.</p>
</div>
  </div>
      </div>

  <ul class="links inline"><li class="comment-reply first"><a href="/comment/reply/114896/861567">Reply to Sam Milnes</a></li>
